         <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">

<ab><lb n="1"/>  <persName type="emperor"><w>Αὐτοκράτο<lb n="2" break="no"/>ρα</w>  <name nymRef="#Καῖσαρ">Καίσαρα</name>    <space extent="1" unit="character"/>  <lb n="3"/> <persName type="emperor"><w lemma="θεός">θεοῦ</w> <name nymRef="#Τραιανός">Τραια<space extent="1" unit="character"/>  <lb n="4" break="no"/>νοῦ</name>  <name nymRef="#Παρθικός">Παρθι<space extent="1" unit="character"/>  <lb n="5" break="no"/>κοῦ</name> <add place="overstrike"><w lemma="υἱός">υἱὸν</w></add> <persName type="emperor"><w lemma="θεός">θεοῦ</w>  <lb n="6"/><name nymRef="#Νέρβα">Νέρουα</name></persName></persName> <w>υἱω<space extent="1" unit="character"/>  <lb n="7" break="no"/>νὸν</w>  <persName type="emperor"><name nymRef="#Τραιανός">Τραια<space extent="1" unit="character"/>  <lb n="8" break="no"/>νον</name>  <name nymRef="#Ἁδριανός">Ἁδρια<space extent="1" unit="character"/>  <lb n="9" break="no"/>νὸν</name>  <w lemma="σεβαστός">Σεβασ<space extent="1" unit="character"/>  <lb n="10" break="no"/>τὸν</w></persName></persName>  <w lemma="ὁ">ὁ</w>  <w>Δῆμος</w></ab>
</div>
         <div type="apparatus">
            <p>l. 5, <foreign xml:lang="grc">ΥΙΟΝ</foreign> cut over <foreign xml:lang="grc">ΥΙΩ</foreign>
            </p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>Imperator Caesar Trajanus Hadrianus Augustus, son of (the) god Trajanus conqueror of the Parthians, grandson of (the) god Nerva. The People (put up his statue).</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>This base is approximately a pair with <ref type="iAph" target="">1311</ref> (=77.34) (dedication to Nerva). A further dedication from the same building, to Antoninus Pius (<ref type="iAph" target="">1300</ref>=80.24) is a little different in style. Were all these among the <foreign xml:lang="grc">τειμαὶ Σεβαστῶν</foreign> claimed by Diogenes, who built the gate? If so, he was precipitate in claiming to have dedicated them. Should the Nerva be taken to be as late as the latest in the group? If so, which—Antoninus Pius?</p>
         </div>
         <div type="bibliography" n="none">
            <p>Unpublished.</p>
         </div>
